passages.text: Al glue for opportunity - assume coverage at Overweight

CY25 and CY26 growth will be supported by industry tailwinds like the Windows 10 refresh and AI infrastructure supply. Despite a projected slowdown in FY25 top- line momentum through 2H, profitability is expected to improve with a shift back to historical revenue composition. Our earnings revisions are minimal, reflecting slight top- line slowing but improved profitability. The company's valuation remains undemanding, with a price target increase to A\$10.30, maintaining an Overweight position. Price target A\$10.30. Overweight. With this note we transfer coverage of Dicker Data to Michael James.

- Tailwinds support growth in CY25 & CY26. FY25 gross sales guidance implies a slowing in top-line momentum, however, there are a number of points worth noting. Firstly, 2H25 starts lapping a stronger pcp where DDR landed a number of larger enterprise deals. Secondly, DDR remains exposed to a number of industry tailwinds presenting upside to guidance, including: 1) Windows 10 refresh cycle and uptake of higher value products; 2) AI infrastructure supply (on today's earnings call management recalled quoting a number of large-scale deals in 1H, none of which materialised); 3) tailwinds for SMB from improvements - including at the margin.

- Margin considerations: A higher Enterprise sales mix was a drag on margins through 1H25, with gross margins down \(\sim 70\) bps y/y to \(9.1\%\) . Positively, this margin compression was offset by lower CODB, with EBITDA margins falling 24bps in comparison. This revenue mix shift had been pre-flagged into the result, and DDR have noted they expect "profitability growth" to improve and a reversion to historical revenue composition (an increasing contribution from SMB and mid-market segments). At the mid-point, FY25 guidance implies \(\sim 35\) bps of sequential PBT margin improvement in 2H, which remains slightly below the recent historical average.

- Cash-flow and balance sheet: Cash conversion was very strong through the half, with a number of moving parts. Higher receivables (in-line with the acceleration in revenue growth) and an inventory build were more than offset by an increased payables balance. The net effect was positive, and we expect these movements to normalise into 2H25. Nonetheless, strong free cash flow saw net decline reduce through the half.

- Earnings & valuation: Our revisions are minimal (FY25 / FY26 PBT flat / \(-2\%\) ) and reflect the 1H25 beat vs. JPMf and the mid-point of FY25 guidance across gross revenue and PBT margins. We assume a slight slowing in top-line momentum, offset by profitability. For FY26, our PBT margins increase to \(3.6\%\) in FY26 and top-line growth slowing to \(+4\%\) . Headline multiples remain undemanding, with DDR trading slightly below its trailing two and three year average multiples. We roll our price target forward to Jun-26; with the net impact of this and our earnings changes a \(1\%\) increase to our PT to A\$10.30. Overweight.

Dicker Data is the largest value- added IT distributor in Australia and the second- largest in New Zealand. Since listing in 2011, DDR has grown its revenues over 5x, driven by underlying growth in the IT industry, market- share gains and opportunistic acquisitions. Near- term, DDR's outlook is impacted by: 1) an elevated inventory balance and working capital intensity; and 2) a slowdown in direct corporate IT spend on end- user computing. In addition, the softness is being partially offset by DDR's diversified business mix. Thus, although we remain cautious near- term, we see opportunity for a recovery in growth into CY25.
Our Jun- 26 price target of A\$10.30 is based on our DCF- based valuation. Key inputs: beta 1.2, WACC \(8.9\%\) TGR \(2.5\%\)
